Road Types¶

Key points of this script:

  • Find the type of road for each road in our dataset so as to add a new feature that we will use later in the regression;
  • Road type classification;
  • Find the city of each street (in our case it can be Ascoli, Roma, Grottaferrata, Frascati and Fregene) in order to facilitate the manual analysis we have done to identify the type of road;
  • Looking at the acceleration graphically, we remove the outliers;

The same analysis will be repeated twice: once for a csv file containing all the roads obtained from measurements taken with the Iphone and the other for the file obtained from the Android phone.

s.remove(np.nan) 
# It may happen that the code was not able to find the name of the street from the latitude and longitude and 
# consequently these are indicated with "nan" and therefore we eliminate them.

Geopy makes easy for Python developers to locate the coordinates of addresses, cities, countries, and landmarks across the globe using third-party geocoders and other data sources. Geopy includes geocoder classes for the OpenStreetMap Nominatim.

Geocoders each define at least a geocode method, for resolving a location from a string, and may define a reverse method, which resolves a pair of coordinates to an address.

In [7]:
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim

street= {} # We put here all the street for which we can retreive the type of road and the city
error = []  # We put here all the street for which we cannot retreive the type of road 
geolocator = Nominatim()

for i in s:
    if (i not in street) and (i not in error):
        print(i)
        t = tuple(data.loc[data.Street == i][['Latitude', 'Longitude']].iloc[0]) 
        # Inside the data a street can be repeat more than one, therefore we take it only once

        location = geolocator.reverse(t) # Reverse method, which resolves a pair of coordinates to an address
        # Thanks the using try & except, we try to retreive the information regarding the different roads
        # but we saw that needed information are in different dictionaries, so using this method we solve the problem
        try:
            town = location.raw['address']['town']
        except:
            try:
                town = location.raw['address']['village']
            except:
                try:
                    town = location.raw['address']['suburb']
                except:
                    town = location.raw['address']['city']
            
        try:
            st = location.raw['address']['road']
        except:
            st = i

        location = geolocator.geocode(st + ' ' + town)
        try:
            street[i] = (location.raw['type'], town) # Save the type of road and the city where it is located
        except:
            print('AHIA',i) # In the case we do
            error.append(i) # Save in this list the streets for which we are not able to obtain the needed information

In case we had more errors (as will occur later for the Android file), the following code allows to understand if the road for which we do not have the necessary information can be dropped or not.

The logic followed is the following:

1) For each street in the "errors" list we check how many of our measurements we have in the dataset:

- If this number is less than 1000 means that we have very little data to analyze on that road and therefore we drop it. 
- This reasoning can no longer be followed if we have so many surveys because this would mean losing a large amount of data to analyze.

2) For the routes we cannot eliminate, we try to manually replace the type of road by searching the Internet.

In [10]:
# We delete small "errors"

s = 0
l = []
for i in error:
    if len(data.loc[data.Street == i]) > 1000:
        l.append(i)
    print(i,len(data.loc[data.Street == i]))
    s += len(data.loc[data.Street == i])

Subsequently we create a new dataset with three columns that indicate respectively the name of the road, the type of road and the city.

Because of the different try & except previously used in the code to identify the city to which the streets belong, sometimes instead of having memorized the name of the city (i.e. "Roma") we have memorized the town hall (i.e., "Roma Municipio I"). If this occurs, we replace it with the name of the city (i.e. "Roma")

We have decided not to have many different types of roads. In our dataset you will find the following types of roads (OpenStreetMaps):

  • Primary: A major highway linking large towns, in developed countries normally with 2 lanes. Definition for Italy "Strada Statale (SS) or Strada Regionale (SR)"
  • Residential: street or road generally used for local traffic within settlement.
  • Secondary: highway which is not part of a major route, but nevertheless forming a link in the national route network.
  • Tertiary: this tag is used for roads connecting smaller settlements, and within large settlements for roads connecting local centres.
  • Motorway: belongs to expressways (Limited-access roads and grade-separated highways). Definition for Italy "Autostrada, compresi i raccordi autostradali come le tangenziali di Milano e il Grande Raccordo Anulare di Roma."

Therefore,in the case that a road was identified with another type we changed its type with one of the above list. Obviously, this change was not made casually but based on online documentation. This was made to not have too many different types: both to reduce the number of columns that will be created later with getdummies and also because the division into roads in OpenStreetMaps is very detailed and for our analysis we need more aggregated rather than specific data. In fact, for instance, we reported the roads that presented as "school" type in another type ("residential").

"OUTLIERS"¶

When the phone is placed horizontally or vertically and is not subject to solicitations (jolts) the accelerometer sensor is affected by gravity which measures ($9.8 m/s^2$). Therefore, we are going to manually see all those measurements (and therefore trips) for which the acceleration does not respect what was said. In these cases it could happen that the phone has been moved, used or the phone's accelerometer has not worked well.

In [26]:
# For each street in our dataframe we save a list with all the accelerations and 
# therefore we consider in the same list also several trips made on the same road
m ={} 
for i in complete.Street.unique():
    m[i] = complete[complete.Street == i].Acc.mean()
In [27]:
# Save in "s" all the street for which there are accelerations greater than 10 or less than 9
s = []
for i in m.keys():
    if (m[i] < 9) or m[i] > 10 :
        s.append(i)
In [28]:
len(s) # How many are these streets?

Now let's look graphically at each of these 43 roads that have different values from those we expected for acceleration. Different situations that can be noticed from the following graphs:

1) There are some jolts: we cannot remove them from the analysis because they are just what we need! They help us to understand if the road is in good condition or not and therefore if the car has taken holes or not.

2) "Bad" measurements: as already mentioned before, in these cases the phone could have been moved or the accelerometer did not work properly.

From the graphs is what we noticed and removed from our dataframe:

  • "Via delle Piave", "Via Fico", "Via Pontoglio", they have too few measurements (about 15 each). Therefore we have decided to eliminate them because we do not know if the phone has malfunctioned or if the car has passed only a few moments on such a street. Since we cannot know it and we would lose only very little data, we preferred to remove it.

  • "Via Seminara" has a strange trend, we eliminate it.

  • "Via G. Delitala" from the graph it can be seen how the phone was not positioned well at the beginning of the measurement and therefore we removed only that "wrong" part of the measurements.

  • "Via della Conciliazione", even if with few measurements we have decided to keep it because it is a street with "sapietrini" and we do not have many in our dataset.
